    <!-- French Advanced Answer's Explanations -->
    <string-array name="french_advanced_explanations">

        <!-- Explanation_1 -->
        <item>\'j\'ai mangé\' uses the auxiliary \'avoir\' and the past participle \'mangé\', which is the passé composé.</item>

        <!-- Explanation_2 -->
        <item>\'que\' is used as a direct object relative pronoun.</item>

        <!-- Explanation_3 -->
        <item>\'bien que\' is a conjunction that always requires the subjunctive mood.</item>

        <!-- Explanation_4 -->
        <item>\'Je serais allé\' is the conditionnel passé.</item>

        <!-- Explanation_5 -->
        <item>Both \'néanmoins\' and \'cependant\' mean \'nevertheless\' or \'however\'.</item>

        <!-- Explanation_6 -->
        <item>Adjectives ending in -eux usually change to -euse in the feminine.</item>

        <!-- Explanation_7 -->
        <item>\'les arbres\' is the plural of \'l\'arbre\'.</item>

        <!-- Explanation_8 -->
        <item>\'venir\' is one of the DR MRS VANDERTRAMP verbs that take \'être\'.</item>

        <!-- Explanation_9 -->
        <item>The imparfait stem is found by taking the \'nous\' form of the present tense (finissons) and removing -ons.</item>

        <!-- Explanation_10 -->
        <item>After verbs of belief in the affirmative, the indicative is used.</item>

    </string-array>



